04590nam a22007815i 9781501722295DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017222957 a10.7591/97815017222952doi  a(DE-B1597)514870  a(OCoLC)1083594250  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPSY0260002bisacsh04a401/.412231 aBracher, Mark, eauthor.10aLacan, Discourse, and Social Change :bA Psychoanalytic Cultural Criticism /cMark Bracher. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tIntroduction: For a Response-Centered Psychoanalytic Cultural Criticism -- tPART I. Theory -- t1. Desire in Discourse -- t2. Social Change and the Ethics of Critical Discourse -- tPART II. Practice -- t3. Pornography -- t4. Antiabortionist Discourse -- t5. Political Campaign Rhetoric -- t6. Heart of Darkness -- t7. "To Autumn" -- tEPILOGUE -- tW0RKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConvinced that cultural criticism need not merely be an academic exercise but can help improve people's lives, Mark Bracher proposes a method of cultural criticism which is based on the principles of psychoanalytic treatment and which aims to alter subjectivity and behavior.In this forceful and engagingly written book, Bracher first accounts for the failure of contemporary cultural criticism to achieve significant social impact. He then offers a model of analysis that draws on Lacan's theoretical insights into the structure of subjectivity and the psychological functions of discourse, asserting that the use of this model can promote collective psychological change. While cultural criticism has generally focused on texts, Bracher instead analyzes audiences' actual responses-to a variety of discourses from "high" as well as popular culture: the political speeches of Ronald Reagan and Jesse Jackson, anti-abortion propaganda, pornography, Keats's "To Autumn," and Conrad's Heart of Darkness. Through analyzing these responses, Bracher is able to uncover the unconscious identifications and fantasies of the respondents-an intervention that, he argues, has the potential for altering subjectivity. In his view, such a method of cultural criticism is both unusually powerful and ethnically defensible, since instead of attacking or upholding a group's values, it reveals the psychological conflicts manifest in responses to particular texts.Lacan, Discourse, and Social Change will be essential reading for students as well as specialists in such fields as cultural criticism, feminist theory, literary theory, psychoanalytic criticism, reader-response criticism, reader-response criticism, and Lacanian theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aSocial change. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501722295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501722295.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG